## Loose Coupling using Interfaces

---

### 📌 What the Diagram Says

```
Loose Coupling → Using Interfaces

Student → Pen   → implements → Writer (interface)
          Pencil →           ↗
```

`Student` depends on a `Writer` — not on `Pen` or `Pencil` directly. Either can be swapped in without changing `Student`.

---

### 🧠 Why Interfaces = Loose Coupling

|          Tight Coupling       |          Loose Coupling         |
|-------------------------------|---------------------------------|
| `Student` directly uses `Pen` | `Student` uses `Writer` interface |
| Change tool → change Student code | Change tool → zero change in Student |
| Hard to test/swap | Easy to swap `Pen` ↔ `Pencil` |

---

### ✅ Full Code

#### 📄 Writer.java (Interface)
```java
package com.example;

public interface Writer {
    void write();
}
```

---

#### 📄 Pen.java
```java
package com.example;

public class Pen implements Writer {

    @Override
    public void write() {
        System.out.println("Writing with Pen...");
    }
}
```

---

#### 📄 Pencil.java
```java
package com.example;

public class Pencil implements Writer {

    @Override
    public void write() {
        System.out.println("Writing with Pencil...");
    }
}
```

---

#### 📄 Student.java
```java
package com.example;

public class Student {

    // Depends on INTERFACE, not on Pen or Pencil directly
    private Writer writer;

    // Setter injection
    public void setWriter(Writer writer) {
        this.writer = writer;
    }

    public void study() {
        System.out.print("Student is studying → ");
        writer.write();   // doesn't care if it's Pen or Pencil
    }
}
```

---

#### 📄 beans.xml
```xml
<beans ...>

    <bean id="pen"    class="com.example.Pen"/>
    <bean id="pencil" class="com.example.Pencil"/>

    <!-- Inject Pen today -->
    <bean id="student" class="com.example.Student" autowire="byType">
        <!-- Spring injects whichever Writer bean is active -->
    </bean>

    <!-- To switch to Pencil: just comment out pen bean, uncomment pencil -->

</beans>
```

> To switch from `Pen` to `Pencil` — **zero changes in Student.java**. Only XML changes. That's loose coupling.

---

#### 📄 App.java
```java
package com.example;

import org.springframework.context.ApplicationContext;
import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationContext;

public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ApplicationContext ctx =
            new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");

        Student s = (Student) ctx.getBean("student");
        s.study();
    }
}
```

#### 🖥️ Output (with Pen)
```
Student is studying → Writing with Pen...
```
#### 🖥️ Output (with Pencil — just swap the bean)
```
Student is studying → Writing with Pencil...
```

---

### 📌 Spring Boot Version (@Autowired + @Component)

```java
// Writer.java
public interface Writer {
    void write();
}

// Pen.java
@Component
public class Pen implements Writer {
    public void write() {
        System.out.println("Writing with Pen...");
    }
}

// Student.java
@Component
public class Student {

    @Autowired
    private Writer writer;  // Spring injects Pen (or Pencil) automatically

    public void study() {
        writer.write();
    }
}
```

> If both `Pen` and `Pencil` are `@Component`, Spring gets confused (two beans of same type `Writer`) → use `@Qualifier` to resolve:

```java
@Autowired
@Qualifier("pen")       // tells Spring: inject the Pen bean specifically
private Writer writer;
```

---

### 🔑 Key Takeaway

```
Tight  → Student uses Pen directly     → change tool = change Student
Loose  → Student uses Writer interface → change tool = zero change in Student
```

> This is the **Dependency Inversion Principle** (the D in SOLID) — depend on abstractions, not concretions. Spring's DI is built exactly on this idea.
